dismissalText.commentary: Grant Elliott lbw b Jordan 32 (15b 3x4 2x6 29m) SR: 213.33

dismissalComment.html: full and straight, Elliott shuffling across his stumps trying to flick leg side, misses and is given out lbw! Looked straight enough, umpire Davis raising the finger, Elliott declines the review after consulting with his partner but that looked good live. Yorker length, angled in, caught Elliott on the boot and surely that was going on to hit leg stump at least

dismissalText.commentary: Luke Ronchi c †Buttler b Finn 33 (16b 2x4 3x6 22m) SR: 206.25

dismissalComment.html: steps to leg, tries to slap a back of a length ball over the off side and gets a thin edge behind! Useful wicket for England because Ronchi was looking very dangerous but here has just miscued a cut stroke and got a feather edge through to Buttler. Some relief for England

dismissalText.commentary: Eoin Morgan c Elliott b McClenaghan 88 (47b 6x4 6x6 86m) SR: 187.23

dismissalComment.html: massive moment! Morgan finds deep point. He came down the pitch, aimed in the air over the off side again but got it too square and Elliott barely had to move on the boundary

dismissalText.commentary: Alex Hales c Boult b Santner 54 (49b 6x4 3x6 62m) SR: 110.2

dismissalComment.html: tries a slog sweep from outside off and Hales picks out deep midwicket! Straight to the fielder a few yards inside the rope and an easy catch for Trent Boult. England losing wickets quickly here to kill their early momentum. Hales was well set but just didn't get enough of this, it was a bit of a top edge and never threatened to clear the boundary. A few strokes finding the fielders and England are suddenly in trouble

dismissalComment.html: aims off side with all the fielders up but doesn't get all of it and finds mid-off jogging back! Slightly off balance trying to swing over the off side and didn't time this at all and Brendon McCullum went back a few yards to take an easy catch

headshotImage.caption: Adil Rashid player page headshot cutout, 2021
headshotImage.longCaption: Adil Rashid player page headshot cutout, 2021

dismissalComment.html: slapped down the ground has Rashid done this here, no!! Long-on come around to take the catch but he's running over the rope so throws it back and then another catch! What a superb piece of fielding and surely that's the game. Tim Southee with the initial catch, realised he was going over the rope so flicked the ball back at the last second but Boult was there in time to reach up with a left-hand and make the second grab. What a bit of work, typically brilliant from New Zealand
there's the breakthrough for New Zealand! And it's that man Boult. Wasn't a great delivery, short of a length and angled across Buttler who went for the cut and got a thin toe end low to Ronchi

A brief flurry from Stokes but perhaps not enough for this chase. He had a fair old swing once more here but nicked off here trying to belt another ball away, thin outside edge with Stokes slightly off balance and it was an easy catch for Ronchi

dismissalComment.html: slapped down the ground has Rashid done this here, no!! Long-on come around to take the catch but he's running over the rope so throws it back and then another catch! What a superb piece of fielding and surely that's the game. commentTextItems.html: length ball, swing and a miss

commentPostTextItems.html: Another amazing game and we have three more to come. Sunday at the Ageas Bowl is the next stop, join us at 10am BST for that one. From Gnasher and myself Alex Winter, bye for now...

Presentation time. Ross Taylor for Man of the Match do you think? Indeed he is. "I was probably trying a little too hard in the Test series but here I'm just concentrating on going out to express myself and so far so good."

Eoin Morgan: "Epic game to play in, the style of cricket we emulated today, I am very proud of. Our fielding was a little disappointing but credit to New Zealand for the way they structured their innings. The chase wasn't a problem for us, it was a case of keeping that up into the late 30s, early 40s overs. When you chase a big score the manner in which you play and the way you take the game to the opposition is important. I struck it well today and it's close to my best again. The mood in the camp is superb. Personally I think D/L will change as the game changes but we were just glad we got back out there. It's such exciting cricket to play."

Brendon McCullum: "I was terrified at times! England are playing a totally different brand of cricket to what they have played recently. Credit to us for holding our nerve at the end there. I though 398 was a good start but the wicket was excellent. There were times when I though we were in front but they came back at us. The weather helped us but it was a tremendous game of cricket. Kane was superb and Ross combined with a few partnerships to accelerate the score, it was outstanding from Ross and we knew we needed a big score and he delivered. The next three games promises to be cracking cricket again. The crowds in the games to come should be excited."

The Kiwis put up a superb innings having won the toss. It was all-go from ball one yet again with Brendon McCullum firing before Kane Williamson and Ross Taylor took over in a superb stand with Taylor going through to a brilliant century - his best for some time really. Unlike the first rubber, this was excellent batting from New Zealand and that's where they have ultimately won the game, despite England's game pursuit, a mention also for their outstanding fielding, in particular that late catch...

New Zealand level the series in an outstanding game. Another belter of a wicket has seen the highest aggregate of runs in an ODI in England. Remarkable once again. England made 400 on Tuesday and were going exceptionally well in pursuit of the target here, only for the rain to cut short their momentum and they were left with a nigh-on impossible target with those revised conditions. Who knows what might have happened without that rain? All we know is that New Zealand have won and the series heads to Southampton on Sunday all square...

full toss wide of off stump, Finn whacks it wide of midwicket
plunked down the ground, to long-off and that will do it, just a single
full outside off, slapped to deep cover and they come back for two

commentPostTextItems.html: Jordan is in pain here...

commentPreTextItems.html: So it's now 24 to win from six balls and Grant Elliott to bowl and Steven Finn on strike, surely there's no final twist in this?

commentTextItems.html: full between the batsman and stumps, Finn swings and misses, Jordan runs a bye and Finn scrambles up the other end in time

commentTextItems.html: what a shot, step across the stumps and flicks this from outside off through square leg, spotted the gap and found the rope

commentPostTextItems.html: Grant Elliot and Mitchell Santner have come down the stairs for a few warm-up deliveries so it looks like those two will bowl the final two overs. The players are now gathered on the outfield and now back comes the batsman to big cheers. Here we go then, Tim Southee with one delivery left. 34 in 13 balls the target...

Clarissa: "Aren't the overs/bowler also being reduced? If so, Southee is bowled out after this ball." Very good point, we're yet to get confirmation of that situation. Ah, here we are. Now only one bowler can bowl 10 overs, which Trent Boult has already done, so McCullum will indeed have to find someone else to bowl which perhaps gives England a better chance but it is still a huge ask but at least the players will get to finish such a brilliant game properly...

8.50pm Looks like it has now stopped raining so fingers crossed we should be able to get some more cricket but we are about to start losing overs so the chase will be trimmed slightly. And we have news, a restart at 9.10pm with 379 to win in 46 overs so another 13 balls to get 34 runs. Safe to say that has not worked in England's favour. Six of those deliveries can be bowled by Tim Southee and Brendon McCullum only has another over to find instead of trying to fiddle through the final six overs of this match, so maybe a break for the tourists with this rain delay...

In the WC England scored 1307 runs in 241 overs..In this series already they have scored 753 in 93 overs....!!! #LoveIt

— Michael Vaughan (@MichaelVaughan) June 12, 2015
<script async src="//platform.twitter.com/widgets.js" charset="utf-8"></script>

8.35pm Still raining I'm afraid so no restart imminent. We have until 8.51pm before we start losing overs and the ultimate cut-off time is 9.15pm. But having said that, the groundstaff are out there trying to be busy and it does look as if it might have now stopped raining. Remarkable two minutes here! And there's applause as the covers begin to be peeled back. But now the fourth umpire Michael Gough puts his umbrella back up!

8.20pm And now the rain takes the players off! England nine behind on D/L at this stage. We were expecting some heavy rain showers and unfortunately one has hit us. We have a half-hour grace period before we start losing overs...

commentTextItems.html: similar area, Plunkett carves this to deep cover
full again, this is driven out wide of deep cover but Rashid slips so they can't even consider the second

commentPostTextItems.html: Pretty heavy rain now, 355 the D/L at the end of this over...

commentTextItems.html: similar ball, this driven to extra-cover, they run regardless and get home

commentPostTextItems.html: Highest score by an England side batting second in an ODI now...

commentTextItems.html: full outside off and just inside the guideline, that is Southee's very own delivery
fires this into the pads, Rashid looking to turn it to leg gets struck on the pad and the keeper is able to field

commentPostTextItems.html: England remarkably keeping this alive, unreal chase...

dismissalComment.html: back of a length just outside off, Guptill pulls and picks out short midwicket! Trap set there by Eoin Morgan and Guptill has been taken as planned. Going for a paddle pull, not really a full-bloodied stroke, but it was still struck firmly and it was a very smart catch from Chris Jordan going to his left, a good height for him and he held on well

headshotImage.longCaption: Ben Stokes player page headshot cutout, 2021

headshotImage.caption: Liam Plunkett player page headshot cutout, 2021
headshotImage.longCaption: Liam Plunkett player page headshot cutout, 2021

dismissalText.commentary: Kane Williamson c Plunkett b Stokes 93 (88b 12x4 1x6 121m) SR: 105.68

dismissalComment.html: caught at mid-on off a full toss, which is called no-ball on field! Williamson taken by surprise, the ball dips on him, skews it without any timing and it's well caught by Plunkett diving forward...it goes up to the third umpire, who rules it's below waist height so it's given out

dismissalText.commentary: Grant Elliott lbw b Jordan 32 (15b 3x4 2x6 29m) SR: 213.33

dismissalComment.html: full and straight, Elliott shuffling across his stumps trying to flick leg side, misses and is given out lbw! Looked straight enough, umpire Davis raising the finger, Elliott declines the review after consulting with his partner but that looked good live. Yorker length, angled in, caught Elliott on the boot and surely that was going on to hit leg stump at least

dismissalText.commentary: Luke Ronchi c †Buttler b Finn 33 (16b 2x4 3x6 22m) SR: 206.25

dismissalComment.html: steps to leg, tries to slap a back of a length ball over the off side and gets a thin edge behind! Useful wicket for England because Ronchi was looking very dangerous but here has just miscued a cut stroke and got a feather edge through to Buttler. Some relief for England

dismissalText.commentary: Jason Roy c Taylor b NL McCullum 39 (37b 6x4 0x6 49m) SR: 105.4

dismissalComment.html: picks him out! The reverse sweep brings his downfall, didn't keep the ball down and Taylor did not have to move an inch at short third man

headshotImage.caption: Mitchell Santner player page headshot cutout, 2021
headshotImage.longCaption: Mitchell Santner player page headshot cutout, 2021

dismissalText.commentary: Alex Hales c Boult b Santner 54 (49b 6x4 3x6 62m) SR: 110.2

dismissalComment.html: tries a slog sweep from outside off and Hales picks out deep midwicket! Straight to the fielder a few yards inside the rope and an easy catch for Trent Boult. England losing wickets quickly here to kill their early momentum. Hales was well set but just didn't get enough of this, it was a bit of a top edge and never threatened to clear the boundary. A few strokes finding the fielders and England are suddenly in trouble

headshotImage.caption: Mitchell Santner player page headshot cutout, 2021
headshotImage.longCaption: Mitchell Santner player page headshot cutout, 2021

dismissalText.commentary: Joe Root c NL McCullum b Santner 6 (10b 0x4 0x6 11m) SR: 60

dismissalComment.html: he's got him! That's a huge wicket for Santner. Root getting too far under this slog-sweep, getting more height than distance, he had to reach for it a little. Nathan McCullum takes a well-judged catch at midwicket

dismissalText.commentary: Eoin Morgan c Elliott b McClenaghan 88 (47b 6x4 6x6 86m) SR: 187.23

dismissalComment.html: massive moment! Morgan finds deep point. He came down the pitch, aimed in the air over the off side again but got it too square and Elliott barely had to move on the boundary

headshotImage.longCaption: Ben Stokes player page headshot cutout, 2021

dismissalText.commentary: Ben Stokes c †Ronchi b McClenaghan 28 (17b 2x4 1x6 23m) SR: 164.7

dismissalComment.html: backs away to leg and tries to swing a full delivery through the off side but edges behind! Healthy edge to the keeper and the change of bowling works. A brief flurry from Stokes but perhaps not enough for this chase. He had a fair old swing once more here but nicked off here trying to belt another ball away, thin outside edge with Stokes slightly off balance and it was an easy catch for Ronchi

dismissalText.commentary: Jos Buttler c †Ronchi b Boult 41 (38b 4x4 1x6 42m) SR: 107.89

dismissalComment.html: there's the breakthrough for New Zealand! And it's that man Boult. Wasn't a great delivery, short of a length and angled across Buttler who went for the cut and got a thin toe end low to Ronchi

dismissalText.commentary: Adil Rashid c Boult b NL McCullum 34 (26b 6x4 0x6 42m) SR: 130.76

dismissalComment.html: slapped down the ground has Rashid done this here, no!! Long-on come around to take the catch but he's running over the rope so throws it back and then another catch! What a superb piece of fielding and surely that's the game. Tim Southee with the initial catch, realised he was going over the rope so flicked the ball back at the last second but Boult was there in time to reach up with a left-hand and make the second grab. What a bit of work, typically brilliant from New Zealand
